The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Dharampal Satyapal Limited (DS group), a food and beverage major, is planning major diversifications with investments amounting to Rs 325 crore. The company will also enter the confectionery market through its joint venture with Lotte Co, Japan. ?We have already commissioned a unit in the northeast to produce packaged fruit juices, which would start production soon,? DS group president Ashok Aggarwal said. The company is in the process of acquiring land in Uttaranchal to set up a facility for its joint venture company ? Lotte DS Ltd ? which is expected to become operational by 2006.

 Hexaware Technologies Limited has bagged an order worth $1.2 million from a global insurance company based in the UK. Hexaware has been selected as a partner by the UK insurance company for running and supporting the complex conversion activity to include both the technical conversion suite and data enhancing activities, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.

 Shree Cement has despatched 2,62,000 tonnes of cement in February, a 4.03 per cent dip over the corresponding month of 2004. The company despatched 27,42,000 tonnes in the April-February period against 26,03,000 tonnes in the year-ago period, registering a growth of 5.34 per cent.

 Macneill Engineering Limited will enter the Sri Lankan market by floating a joint venture company with a leading industrial house in Sri Lanka of Shri Vasanthe Senanayake, having interests in shipping and material handling. Forklift trucks and other material handling equipment will be exported to Sri Lanka and assembled in Colombo.

 Elder Pharmaceuticals Ltd has launched NuLife chewing gum, a nicotine replacement therapy product for tobacco cessation. NuLife will be available as a chewing gum in two different varieties, namely GoodKha and Eucomint. 

